TY  - JOUR
AU  - Dutta, Rohan
T1  - Bargaining as a Struggle Between Competing Attempts at Commitment
PY  - 2024
Y1  - 2024/10/01
DO  - 10.1093/restud/rdad106
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 91
IS  - 5
SP  - 2771
EP  - 2805
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - The strategic importance of commitment in bargaining is widely acknowledged. Yet disentangling its role from key features of canonical models, such as proposal power and reputational concerns, is difficult. This paper introduces a model of bargaining with strategic commitment at its core. Following Schelling (1956, The American Economic Review, vol. 46, 281–306), commitment ability stems from the costly nature of concession and is endogenously determined by players’ demands. Agreement is immediate for familiar bargainers, modelled via renegotiation-proofness. The unique prediction at the high concession cost limit provides a strategic foundation for the Kalai bargaining solution. Equilibria with delay feature a form of gradualism in demands.
Y2  - 10/27/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/restud/rdad106
ER  - 



